tracking: dynamic programming (DP).\nThe idea in plain terms: The bit traces a physical path through the formation.\nTVT at one position constrains what TVT can be at the next position; it can't\njump 50 ft in one sample. Most trackers in this competition (particle filters,\nbeam search) use heuristics to exploit this constraint. DP is the brute-force\nalternative: evaluate every possible TVT path through the typewell state space\nand pick the one that best matches the observed GR log, subject to a smoothness\npenalty. No randomness, no pruning, guaranteed global optimum for each parameter\nset. The trade-off is that you discretize the state space (~400 candidate TVT\npositions in a +/-200 ft window around the anchor).\nI ran five configurations with different smoothness settings, from \"stiff\"\n(strongly resist TVT changes between positions, producing smooth paths that\ncapture the broad trend) to \"loose\" (allow rapid TVT changes, producing\n--- hits ---\n1: в•ӯв”Җ Dynamic Programming for TVT Tracking: What Worked, What Didn't, and What thв”Җв•®\n3: в”Ӯ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus в”Ӯ\n12: Dynamic Programming for TVT Tracking: What Worked, What Didn't, and What the Gap\n17: approach to TVT tracking: dynamic programming (DP).\n24: and pick the one that best matches the observed GR log, subject to a smoothness\n34: statistics + GR residuals at various offsets = 24-75 features fed into the same\n35: LightGBM.\n49: Geosteering TVT tracking (this notebook) вҖ” find TVT states that align lateral GR\n50: to typewell GR:\n53: min sum_i [ (GR_obs_i - GR_typewell[state_i])^2 / sigma + mu * |state_i -\n60: \"lateral GR log\", \"reference image\" with \"typewell\", \"shift\" with \"TVT state\",\n62: alignment (Sakoe and Chiba, 1978), sequence decoding (Viterbi, 1967), and\n64: dynamic programming principle. Pure numpy, no Numba, deterministic, ~25 min for\n69: вҖў The Viterbi ensemble mean became the #1 feature by LightGBM ga