github.com/mycarta/rogii-geosteering-toolkit\nSingle LightGBM, no particle filters or stacking. Mid-pack on the leaderboard,\nbut the findings may be useful to others working on this problem:\nвҖў Within-well TVT-Z decoupling. The global TVT-vs-Z correlation is r = -0.96,\nbut within a single lateral it's essentially zero (mean slope +0.057). The\nglobal signal is cross-well structural elevation dominated by build-section\ngeometry. Features based on the global relationship don't work until you\naccount for this.\nвҖў Q-3D tortuosity (Jing et al. 2022) was the most useful domain feature in the\nablation (-0.107 RMSE). High tortuosity = active steering = formation\ndeviating from plan.\nвҖў Signed drilling azimuth matters. Opposite directions along the same line see\n--- hits ---\n3: в”Ӯ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus в”Ӯ\n16: https://www.kaggle.com/code/mycarta/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-toolkit\n20: Single LightGBM, no particle filters or stacking. Mid-pack on the leaderboard,\n29: ablation (-0.107 RMSE). High tortuosity = active steering = formation\n35: RMSE). Well-level features under GroupKFold overfit on cross-well noise.\n37: вҖў Considered Verde's BlockKFold for spatial CV, rejected it. Validation wells\n38: are spatially interleaved with training (interpolation, not extrapolation),\n39: so spatial blocking is more pessimistic than the actual test condition. Used\n40: StratifiedGroupKFold stratified by signed azimuth, median TVT, and spatial\n43: The notebook includes a cumulative ablation table, Phase 1 spatial recon figures\n45: MASS-equivalent-to-NCC pedagogical demo, and a Q-3D tortuosity visualization.\n47: The GitHub repo has the reusable toolkit modules (wellbore tortuosity from XYZ\n\n### discussion_698825.md\nв•ӯв”Җ How Geologists Interpret Wells: Some Helpful Tips в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®\nв”Ӯ Author: Igor Kuvaev | Votes: 51 | Comments: 3 |